- No production, execution, treasury, custody, wallet/signing, financial, provider, settlement, payout, billing or contract-write authority is added.

Status: ESTABLISHED

Scope: Core, Governance, Documentation, Dex, Defi, AxodusAPP, Business, Marketplace, Academy, Mining, ACS, Trading, BBA-Agency, Lottery

Root versioning state: `/opt/Axodus` is not a Git repository. This register is local/unversioned portfolio evidence.

Purpose: add a development maturity dimension alongside organizational maturity.

- L-level: organizational maturity, governance, evidence, readiness and controls.
- D-level: implementation maturity, software surface, validation evidence and integration depth.

No production readiness, execution authority, treasury authority, wallet signing, settlement, payout, trading or on-chain behavior is granted by this register.

## Development Maturity Model

| Level | Name | Criteria |
| --- | --- | --- |
| D0 | Concept Only | Idea, roadmap or documentation only. No meaningful implementation evidence. |
| D1 | Technical Foundation | Project structure, types, schemas, mock data, basic architecture and minimal behavior. |
| D2 | Local Product Functionality | UI, API, SDK, services or workflows operate locally with mock or non-production behavior. |
| D3 | Integrated Functionality | Cross-module integration, read-only providers, real data ingestion, internal ecosystem integration or meaningful user workflows without execution-sensitive production behavior. |
| D3+ | Validated Integrated Functionality | D3-level integration plus fresh build/test/check, explicit boundary enforcement, security review and coherent handoff evidence; still non-production and below controlled execution. |
| D4 | Controlled Execution | Testnet, sandbox or controlled execution workflows with strong non-production constraints. |
| D5 | Production Capability | Production infrastructure, real users, operational controls and explicit production approval. Not assigned without direct evidence. |

## Methodology

The D-level classification uses repository structure, source and test footprint, package scripts, local validation evidence, status documents, maturity assessments, handoffs, product documentation and implemented UI/API/SDK/provider surfaces. It does not rely solely on `.instructions`.

Functional completeness is a conservative estimate of implemented software surface relative to the nucleus's currently documented product scope. It is not a business-readiness, production-readiness or revenue-readiness percentage.

